Enum Constant Detail

X

public static final PLevel.Type X
X axis value in pixels. The X axis points to the right of the screen. It's a left handed coordinate system: the Z axis points upside.

Y

public static final PLevel.Type Y
Y axis value in pixels. The Y axis points to the bottom of the screen.

PRESSURE

public static final PLevel.Type PRESSURE
Range: 0 to 1.

TILT_X

public static final PLevel.Type TILT_X
Angle between the Z axis and the projection of the pen against the X-Z plane. Range: -pi/2 to pi/2 radians.

TILT_Y

public static final PLevel.Type TILT_Y
Angle between the Z axis and the projection of the pen against the Y-Z plane. Range: -pi/2 to pi/2 radians.

SIDE_PRESSURE

public static final PLevel.Type SIDE_PRESSURE
Barrel button or wheel. Range: 0 to 1 towards the pen tip.

Warning: Testing needed. The development team does not have an airbrush to test on all platforms. Please help us giving feedback (start a topic on the help forum):

  • Which operating system are you using?
  • Does the value grow (0 to 1) when the wheel is moved towards the pen tip?
  • Are you using an airbrush or a pen marker?

Pen rotation. Range: 0 to 2*pi clockwise. Warning: Testing needed. The development team does not have a pen marker or 4D mouse to test on all platforms. Please help us giving feedback (start a topic on the help forum):
  • Which operating system are you using?
  • Does the value grow from 0 to 2*pi when the device is moved clockwise?
  • Are you using a pen marker or 4D mouse?

evalAzimuthXAndAltitude

public static void evalAzimuthXAndAltitude(double[] azimuthXAndAltitude,
                                           double tiltX,
                                           double tiltY)
Evaluates the azimuthX and the altitude given the tilt (TILT_X, TILT_Y) values. Where:

azimuthX is the angle between the X axis and the projection of the pen against the X-Y plane. Clockwise direction. Range: -pi/2 and 3*pi/2

And altitude is the angle between the pen and the projection of the pen against the X-Y plane. Range: 0 to pi/2.
